# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ethercat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] A **distributed control system** (**DCS**) is a computerized control system for a process or plant usually with many control loops, in which autonomous controllers are distributed throughout the system, but there is no central operator supervisory control.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] This is in contrast to systems that use centralized controllers; either discrete controllers located at a central control room or within a central computer.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The DCS concept increases reliability and reduces installation costs by localizing control functions near the process plant, with remote monitoring and supervision.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems first emerged in large, high value, safety critical process industries, and were attractive because the DCS manufacturer would supply both the local control level and central supervisory equipment as an integrated package, thus reducing design integration risk.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Today the functionality of Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) and DCS systems are very similar, but DCS tends to be used on large continuous process plants where high reliability and security is important, and the control room is not necessarily geographically remote.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Many machine control systems exhibit similar properties as plant and process control systems do.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The key attribute of a DCS is its reliability due to the distribution of the control processing around nodes in the system.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] This mitigates a single processor failure.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] If a processor fails, it will only affect one section of the plant process, as opposed to a failure of a central computer which would affect the whole process.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] This distribution of computing power local to the field Input/Output (I/O) connection racks also ensures fast controller processing times by removing possible network and central processing delays.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels using computerised control.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Levels 1 and 2 are the functional levels of a traditional DCS, in which all equipment are part of an integrated system from a single manufacturer.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Levels 3 and 4 are not strictly process control in the traditional sense, but where production control and scheduling takes place.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The processor nodes and operator graphical displays are connected over proprietary or industry standard networks, and network reliability is increased by dual redundancy cabling over diverse routes.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] This distributed topology also reduces the amount of field cabling by siting the I/O modules and their associated processors close to the process plant.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be signalled by the output modules.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can be analog signals e.g.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] 4–20 mA DC current loop or two-state signals that switch either "on" or "off", such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] DCSs are connected to sensors and actuators and use setpoint control to control the flow of material through the plant.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] A typical application is a PID controller fed by a flow meter and using a control valve as the final control element.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The DCS sends the setpoint required by the process to the controller which instructs a valve to operate so that the process reaches and stays at the desired setpoint.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Large oil refineries and chemical plants have several thousand I/O points and employ very large DCS.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Processes are not limited to fluidic flow through pipes, however, and can also include things like paper machines and their associated quality controls, variable speed drives and motor control centers, cement kilns, mining operations, ore processing facilities, and many others.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] DCSs in very high reliability applications can have dual redundant processors with "hot" switch over on fault, to enhance the reliability of the control system.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Although 4–20 mA has been the main field signalling standard, modern DCS systems can also support fieldbus digital protocols, such as Foundation Fieldbus, profibus, HART, modbus, PC Link, etc.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Modern DCSs also support neural networks and fuzzy logic applications.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Recent research focuses on the synthesis of optimal distributed controllers, which optimizes a certain H-infinity or the H 2 control criterion.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems (DCS) are dedicated systems used in manufacturing processes that are continuous or batch-oriented.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] However this required a large amount of human oversight to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Effectively this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] These could be distributed around plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The distributed control system was born.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Early minicomputers were used in the control of industrial processes since the beginning of the 1960s.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The IBM 1800, for example, was an early computer that had input/output hardware to gather process signals in a plant for conversion from field contact levels (for digital points) and analog signals to the digital domain.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The first industrial control computer system was built 1959 at the Texaco Port Arthur, Texas, refinery with an RW-300 of the Ramo-Wooldridge Company.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] In 1975, both HONEYWELL and Japanese electrical engineering firm Yokogawa introduced their own independently produced DCS's - TDC 2000 and CENTUM systems, respectively.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] US-based Bristol also introduced their UCS 3000 universal controller in 1975.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] In 1978 Valmet introduced their own DCS system called Damatic (latest web-based generation Valmet DNAe).
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] In 1980, Bailey (now part of ABB) introduced the NETWORK 90 system, Fisher Controls (now part of Emerson Electric) introduced the PROVoX system, Fischer & Porter Company (now also part of ABB) introduced DCI-4000 (DCI stands for Distributed Control Instrumentation).
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The DCS largely came about due to the increased availability of microcomputers and the proliferation of microprocessors in the world of process control.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Computers had already been applied to process automation for some time in the form of both direct digital control (DDC) and setpoint control.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] In the early 1970s Taylor Instrument Company, (now part of ABB) developed the 1010 system, Foxboro the FOX1 system, Fisher Controls the DC2 system and Bailey Controls the 1055 systems.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] All of these were DDC applications implemented within minicomputers (DEC PDP-11, Varian Data Machines, MODCOMP etc.) and connected to proprietary Input/Output hardware.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Sophisticated (for the time) continuous as well as batch control was implemented in this way.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] A more conservative approach was setpoint control, where process computers supervised clusters of analog process controllers.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] A workstation provided visibility into the process using text and crude character graphics.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Availability of a fully functional graphical user interface was a way away.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Central to the DCS model was the inclusion of control function blocks.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Function blocks evolved from early, more primitive DDC concepts of "Table Driven" software.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] One of the first embodiments of object-oriented software, function blocks were self-contained "blocks" of code that emulated analog hardware control components and performed tasks that were essential to process control, such as execution of PID algorithms.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Function blocks continue to endure as the predominant method of control for DCS suppliers, and are supported by key technologies such as Foundation Fieldbus today.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Midac Systems, of Sydney, Australia, developed an objected-oriented distributed direct digital control system in 1982.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The central system ran 11 microprocessors sharing tasks and common memory and connected to a serial communication network of distributed controllers each running two Z80s.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The system was installed at the University of Melbourne.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Digital communication between distributed controllers, workstations and other computing elements (peer to peer access) was one of the primary advantages of the DCS.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Attention was duly focused on the networks, which provided the all-important lines of communication that, for process applications, had to incorporate specific functions such as determinism and redundancy.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] As a result, many suppliers embraced the IEEE 802.4 networking standard.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] This decision set the stage for the wave of migrations necessary when information technology moved into process automation and IEEE 802.3 rather than IEEE 802.4 prevailed as the control LAN.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] In the 1980s, users began to look at DCSs as more than just basic process control.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] A very early example of a Direct Digital Control DCS was completed by the Australian business Midac in 1981–82 using R-Tec Australian designed hardware.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The system installed at the University of Melbourne used a serial communications network, connecting campus buildings back to a control room "front end".
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Each remote unit ran two Z80 microprocessors, while the front end ran eleven Z80s in a parallel processing configuration with paged common memory to share tasks and that could run up to 20,000 concurrent control objects.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] It was believed that if openness could be achieved and greater amounts of data could be shared throughout the enterprise that even greater things could be achieved.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The first attempts to increase the openness of DCSs resulted in the adoption of the predominant operating system of the day: *UNIX*.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] UNIX and its companion networking technology TCP-IP were developed by the US Department of Defense for openness, which was precisely the issue the process industries were looking to resolve.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] As a result, suppliers also began to adopt Ethernet-based networks with their own proprietary protocol layers.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The full TCP/IP standard was not implemented, but the use of Ethernet made it possible to implement the first instances of object management and global data access technology.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The 1980s also witnessed the first PLCs integrated into the DCS infrastructure.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Plant-wide historians also emerged to capitalize on the extended reach of automation systems.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The first DCS supplier to adopt UNIX and Ethernet networking technologies was Foxboro, who introduced the I/A Series system in 1987.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The drive toward openness in the 1980s gained momentum through the 1990s with the increased adoption of commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) components and IT standards.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Probably the biggest transition undertaken during this time was the move from the UNIX operating system to the Windows environment.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] While the realm of the real time operating system (RTOS) for control applications remains dominated by real time commercial variants of UNIX or proprietary operating systems, everything above real-time control has made the transition to Windows.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The introduction of Microsoft at the desktop and server layers resulted in the development of technologies such as OLE for process control (OPC), which is now a de facto industry connectivity standard.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Internet technology also began to make its mark in automation and the world, with most DCS HMI supporting Internet connectivity.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The 1990s were also known for the "Fieldbus Wars", where rival organizations competed to define what would become the IEC fieldbus standard for digital communication with field instrumentation instead of 4–20 milliamp analog communications.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The first fieldbus installations occurred in the 1990s.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Towards the end of the decade, the technology began to develop significant momentum, with the market consolidated around Ethernet I/P, Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA for process automation applications.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Fieldbus technics have been used to integrate machine, drives, quality and condition monitoring applications to one DCS with Valmet DNA system.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The impact of COTS, however, was most pronounced at the hardware layer.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] For years, the primary business of DCS suppliers had been the supply of large amounts of hardware, particularly I/O and controllers.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The initial proliferation of DCSs required the installation of prodigious amounts of this hardware, most of it manufactured from the bottom up by DCS suppliers.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Standard computer components from manufacturers such as Intel and Motorola, however, made it cost prohibitive for DCS suppliers to continue making their own components, workstations, and networking hardware.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] As the suppliers made the transition to COTS components, they also discovered that the hardware market was shrinking fast.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] COTS not only resulted in lower manufacturing costs for the supplier, but also steadily decreasing prices for the end users, who were also becoming increasingly vocal over what they perceived to be unduly high hardware costs.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The traditional DCS suppliers introduced new generation DCS System based on the latest Communication and IEC Standards, which resulting in a trend of combining the traditional concepts/functionalities for PLC and DCS into a one for all solution—named "Process Automation System" (PAS).
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The gaps among the various systems remain at the areas such as: the database integrity, pre-engineering functionality, system maturity, communication transparency and reliability.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] While it is expected the cost ratio is relatively the same (the more powerful the systems are, the more expensive they will be), the reality of the automation business is often operating strategically case by case.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The current next evolution step is called Collaborative Process Automation Systems.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] To compound the issue, suppliers were also realizing that the hardware market was becoming saturated.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The life cycle of hardware components such as I/O and wiring is also typically in the range of 15 to over 20 years, making for a challenging replacement market.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Many of the older systems that were installed in the 1970s and 1980s are still in use today, and there is a considerable installed base of systems in the market that are approaching the end of their useful life.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Developed industrial economies in North America, Europe, and Japan already had many thousands of DCSs installed, and with few if any new plants being built, the market for new hardware was shifting rapidly to smaller, albeit faster growing regions such as China, Latin America, and Eastern Europe.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Because of the shrinking hardware business, suppliers began to make the challenging transition from a hardware-based business model to one based on software and value-added services.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] It is a transition that is still being made today.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The applications portfolio offered by suppliers expanded considerably in the '90s to include areas such as production management, model-based control, real-time optimization, plant asset management (PAM), Real-time performance management (RPM) tools, alarm management, and many others.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] To obtain the true value from these applications, however, often requires a considerable service content, which the suppliers also provide.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Increasingly, and ironically, DCS are becoming centralised at plant level, with the ability to log into the remote equipment.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] This enables operator to control both at enterprise level ( macro ) and at the equipment level (micro), both within and outside the plant, because the importance of the physical location drops due to interconnectivity primarily thanks to wireless and remote access.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] The more wireless protocols are developed and refined, the more they are included in DCS.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] DCS controllers are now often equipped with embedded servers and provide on-the-go web access.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Whether DCS will lead Industrial Internet of Things (IIOT) or borrow key elements from remains to be seen.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] Many vendors provide the option of a mobile HMI, ready for both Android and iOS.
[src:ethercat/distributed-control-system] With these interfaces, the threat of security breaches and possible damage to plant and process are now very real.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The goal during development of EtherCAT was to apply Ethernet for automation applications requiring short data update times (also called cycle times; ≤ 100 μs) with low communication jitter (for precise synchronization purposes; ≤ 1 μs) and reduced hardware costs.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Typical application fields for EtherCAT are machine controls.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] This includes semiconductor tools, metal forming, packaging, injection molding, assembly systems, printing machines, and robotics.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Alternative technologies for networking in the industrial environment include EtherNet/IP, Profinet and Profibus.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] With EtherCAT, the standard Ethernet packet or frame (according to IEEE 802.3) is no longer received, interpreted, and copied as process data at every node.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The EtherCAT slave devices read the data addressed to them while the telegram passes through the device, processing data "on the fly".
[src:ethercat/ethercat] In other words, real-time data and messages are prioritized over more general, less time-sensitive or heavy load data.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Similarly, input data is inserted while the telegram passes through.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] A frame is not completely received before being processed; instead processing starts as soon as possible.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Sending is also conducted with a minimum delay of small bit times.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Typically the entire network can be addressed with just one frame.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The EtherCAT protocol is optimized for process data and is transported directly within the standard IEEE 802.3 Ethernet frame using Ethertype 0x88a4.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] It may consist of several sub-telegrams, each serving a particular memory area of the logical process images that can be up to 4 gigabytes in size.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The data sequence is independent of the physical order of the nodes in the network; addressing can be in any order.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Broadcast, multicast and communication between slaves is possible, but must be initiated by the master device.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] If IP routing is required, the EtherCAT protocol can be inserted into UDP/IP datagrams.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] This also enables any control with Ethernet protocol stack to address EtherCAT systems.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Short cycle times can be achieved since the host microprocessors in the slave devices are not involved in the processing of the Ethernet packets to transfer the process images.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] All process data communication is handled in the slave controller hardware.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Combined with the functional principle this makes EtherCAT a high performance distributed I/O system: Process data exchange with 1000 distributed digital I/O takes about 30 μs, which is typical for a transfer of 125 byte over 100 Mbit/s Ethernet.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Data for and from 100 servo axis can be updated with up to 10 kHz.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Typical network update rates are 1–30 kHz, but EtherCAT can be used with slower cycle times, too, if the DMA load is too high.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The bandwidth utilization is maximized, as each node and each data do not require a separate frame.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Thus, extremely short cycle times of ≤ 100 μs are achievable.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] By using the full-duplex features of 100BASE-TX, effective data rates of more than 100 Mbit/s (> 90% user data rate of 2x100 Mbit/s) can be achieved.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The EtherCAT technology principle is scalable and not bound to 100 Mbit/s.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Using full-duplex Ethernet physical layers, the EtherCAT slave controllers close an open port automatically and return the Ethernet frame if no downstream device is detected.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Slave devices may have one, two, or more ports.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Due to these features EtherCAT enables a multitude of network topologies, including line, tree, ring, star, or any combination thereof.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The protocol also enables a multitude of communication features such as cable redundancy, Hot Connect of segments, change of devices during operation, or even master redundancy with Hot Standby.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Thus the combination of the topology variations and different network architectures, e.g. sub-ordinated or neighboring control systems with consistent synchronization, enables numerous possibilities.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The physics of Ethernet allow a cable length of up to 100 m (300 ft) between two nodes, so the E-bus (LVDS) is only intended for use as the physical layer for modular devices.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] For each cable path, the signal variant can be chosen individually.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] For higher distances, or the complete galvanic isolation between two slaves, fiber optic cables are used.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] With single-mode fiber, distances up to 20 km between two nodes can be bridged.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Since a total of 65,535 nodes per network segment can be connected, the network extension is nearly unlimited.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] For synchronization a distributed clock mechanism is applied, which leads to very low jitter, significantly less than 1 μs, even if the communication cycle jitters, which is equivalent to the IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol standard (PTP).
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Therefore, EtherCAT does not require special hardware in the master device and can be implemented in software on any standard Ethernet MAC, even without dedicated communication coprocessor.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The typical process of establishing a distributed clock is initiated by the master by sending a broadcast to all slaves to a certain address.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Upon reception of this message, all slaves will latch the value of their internal clock twice, once when the message is received and once when it returns (remember EtherCAT has a ring topology).
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The master can then read all latched values and calculate the delay for each slave.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] This process can be repeated as many times as required to reduce jitter and average out values.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Total delays are calculated for each slave depending on their position in the slave-ring and will be uploaded to an offset register.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Finally the master issues a broadcast readwrite on the system clock, which will make the first slave the reference clock and forcing all other slaves to set their internal clock appropriately with the now known offset.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] To keep the clocks synchronised after initialization, the master or slave must regularly send out the broadcast again to counter any effects of speed difference between the internal clocks of each slave.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Each slave should adjust the speed of their internal clock or implement an internal correction mechanism whenever they have to adjust.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The system clock is specified as a 64 bit counter with a base unit of 1ns starting at January 1, 2000, 0:00.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The fast, precise detection of disturbances is one of many diagnostic features of EtherCAT.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Bit errors during transmission are detected reliably by the analysis of the CRC check sum: the 32 bit CRC polynomial has a minimum Hamming distance of 4.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Besides the error detection and localization protocol, the transmission physics and topology of the EtherCAT system allow individual quality monitoring of every single transmission path.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The automated analysis of the according error counters enables the exact localization of critical network segments.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] More info to follow in the chapter titled "Monitoring".
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The device profiles describe the application parameters and functional behavior of the devices, including device-specific state machines.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The following software interfaces are provided for existing device profiles.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Thus, the migration to EtherCAT by adjusting the firmware and the hardware is simplified significantly.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] SERCOS interface is a real-time communication interface, ideal for motion control applications.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The SERCOS profile for servo drives and communication technology are standardized in IEC 61800-7.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] This standard also contains the mapping of the SERCOS servo drive profile to EtherCAT (IEC 61800-7-304).
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Any Ethernet device can be connected within the EtherCAT segment via switch ports.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The Ethernet frames are tunneled via the EtherCAT protocol, as is normal for internet protocols (e.g., TCP/IP, VPN, PPPoE (DSL), etc.).
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The EtherCAT network is fully transparent for the Ethernet devices, and the real-time features of EtherCAT are not disturbed.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] In parallel to the development of EtherCAT, a fieldbus-independent safety protocol has been developed.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] For EtherCAT, it is available as "Safety over EtherCAT" (FSoE = Fail Safe over EtherCAT).
[src:ethercat/ethercat] With FSoE, functional safety with EtherCAT can be realized.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The protocol as well as the implementation are certified by TÜV and meet the requirements of the Safety Integrity Level 3 according to IEC 61508.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Since 2010, Safety over EtherCAT is internationally standardized to IEC 61784-3-12.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] EtherCAT provides a single-channel communication system for transferring safe and non-safe information.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The transport medium is regarded as a black channel, and thus is not included in safety considerations.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] This simple protocol is similar to TFTP (Trivial File Transfer Protocol); it enables file access in a device and a uniform firmware upload to devices across an EtherCAT network.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The protocol has been deliberately specified in a lean manner, so that it can be supported by boot loader programs.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Since EtherCAT uses standard Ethernet frames according to IEEE 802.3, any standard Ethernet tool can be used to monitor the EtherCAT communication.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Additionally, there is free-of-charge parser software for Wireshark (formerly Ethereal, an open source monitoring tool) and the Microsoft network monitor, with which recorded EtherCAT data traffic can be comfortably prepared and displayed.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] By using gateways, existing networks such as CANopen, DeviceNet, or Profibus, can be integrated into the EtherCAT environment seamlessly.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Furthermore, gateways provide a trip-free migration path from a traditional fieldbus to EtherCAT, reducing further investment costs.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Thanks to the performance of EtherCAT, communication with external fieldbus masters is as fast as with traditional cards connected via PCI or other backbone buses.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Since decentralized fieldbus interfaces lead to shorter extensions, they can be operated with even higher baud rates than would have been possible with the traditional architecture.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] EtherCAT Technology Group (ETG) encourages and expects companies that develop EtherCAT products to join ETG, so that they can get an EtherCAT Vendor-ID, get access to the full documentation, to the developers forum and to the slave stack code, that Beckhoff provides free of charge to ETG members.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Masters can be implemented as a software solution on any Ethernet MAC.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Different manufacturers provide code for different operating systems, including several open-source projects.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Due to the relocated mapping on the slave hardware, demands are reduced for CPU performance of the master.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The master already contains the data as a readily sorted process image.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] In order to operate a network, the EtherCAT master requires the cyclic process data structure as well as boot-up commands for each slave device.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] These commands can be exported to an EtherCAT Network Information (ENI) file with the help of an EtherCAT configuration tool, which uses the EtherCAT Slave Information (ESI) files from the connected devices.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Contrary to the operation of standard Ethernet, the slaves process the EtherCAT frames on the fly.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] This requires the use of hardware-integrated EtherCAT Slave Controllers (ESC) in the slaves.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] ESCs are also available as ASICs or based on FPGAs.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Since the beginning of 2012, standard microprocessors with EtherCAT slave interfaces are also available.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] For simple devices, no additional microcontroller is required.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] In more complex devices, however, the communication performance of EtherCAT is nearly independent of the performance of the used controller.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Thus the requirements for the microcontroller are determined by the local application, e.g. the drive control.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] There is a choice of development boards, both from the EtherCAT Slave Controller suppliers and from third party vendors.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] There are also open-source projects for EtherCAT slave device development boards, such as SOES and ArduCAT.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] For the control and regulation of physical processes, high data integrity, data security, and synchronicity is required.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] EtherCAT has been designed especially for these kinds of applications and meets all demands for fast controls.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Modern measurement systems are characterized by multi-channeling, synchronicity, and accuracy.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Due to the advanced protocol features of EtherCAT, efficient synchronous data throughput is assured.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The network features based on Ethernet enable a measurement network with distributed measurement modules.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The EtherCAT Technology Group (ETG) was established in 2003, and is the industrial Ethernet user organization with the most members in the world today.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] A wide range of industrial controls vendors, OEMs, machine builders, and technology organizations from around the world constitute the ETG member roster.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The ETG offers its members implementation support and training, organizes interoperability tests (often called "Plug Fests"), and promotes the development and distribution of the technology, supported by its members and the teams working in offices in Germany, China, Japan, Korea, and North America.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] ETG end users span numerous industries, with machine builders and suppliers of powerful control technology joining forces to support and promote EtherCAT technology.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The variety of industries guarantees optimal preparation of EtherCAT for the widest range of applications.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] System partners give qualified feedback for the simple integration of hardware and software modules in all required equipment classes.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The EtherCAT Conformance Test Tool (CTT), developed with the assistance of ETG member companies, ensures the interoperability and protocol conformity of EtherCAT devices.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The EtherCAT Technology Group (ETG) is an official liaison partner of the IEC (International Electrotechnical Commission) working groups for digital communication.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] The EtherCAT specification was published as IEC/PAS 62407 in 2005, which was removed end of 2007 since EtherCAT had been integrated into the international fieldbus standards IEC 61158 and IEC 61784-2 as well as into the drive profile standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] These IEC standards have been approved unanimously in September and October 2007 and were published as IS (International Standards) later that year.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] In IEC 61800-7, EtherCAT is a standardized communication technology for the SERCOS and CANopen drive profiles (also known as CiA 402).
[src:ethercat/ethercat] EtherCAT is also part of ISO 15745-4, the standard for XML device description.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] Furthermore, SEMI has added EtherCAT to its standards portfolio (E54.20) and approved the technology for usage in semiconductor and flat panel display manufacturing equipment.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] In April 2010, Edition 2 of IEC 61784-3 was accepted, which contains the Safety over EtherCAT Protocol.
[src:ethercat/ethercat] In September 2008, the EtherCAT Installation Profile was submitted to IEC 61784-5.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] A **fieldbus** is a member of a family of industrial digital communication networks used for real-time distributed control.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Fieldbus profiles are standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as IEC 61784/61158.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] A complex automated industrial system is typically structured in hierarchical levels as a distributed control system (DCS).
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In this hierarchy the upper levels for production managements are linked to the direct control level of programmable logic controllers (PLC) via a non-time-critical communications system (e.g.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The fieldbus links the PLCs of the direct control level to the components in the plant at the field level, such as sensors, actuators, electric motors, console lights, switches, valves and contactors.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It also replaces the direct connections via current loops or digital I/O signals.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The requirements for a fieldbus are therefore time-critical and cost-sensitive.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Since the new millennium, a number of fieldbuses based on Real-time Ethernet have been established.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] These have the potential to replace traditional fieldbuses in the long term.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] A fieldbus is an industrial network system for real-time distributed control.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It is a way to connect instruments in a manufacturing plant.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] A fieldbus works on a network structure which typically allows daisy-chain, star, ring, branch, and tree network topologies.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Previously, computers were connected using RS-232 (serial connections) by which only two devices could communicate.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This reduces both the length of and total number of cables required.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Furthermore, since devices that communicate through a fieldbus require a microprocessor, multiple points are typically provided by the same device.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Some fieldbus devices now support control schemes such as PID control on the device-side instead of forcing the controller to do the processing.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The most important motivation to use a fieldbus in a distributed control system is to reduce the cost for installation and maintenance of the installation without losing the high availability and reliability of the automation system.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The goal is to use a two wire cable and simple configuration for field devices from different manufacturers.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Depending on the application, the number of sensors and actuators vary from hundreds in one machine up to several thousands distributed over a large plant.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The history of the fieldbus demonstrates how these goals have been approached over time.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Arguably the precursor field bus technology is HP-IB as described in IEEE 488 in 1975.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] "It became known as the General Purpose Interface Bus (GPIB), and became a de facto standard for automated and industrial instrument control".
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The GPIB has its main application in automated measurements with instruments from different manufacturers.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It is a parallel bus with a cable and connector with 24 wires, limited to a maximal cable length of 20 metres.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The oldest commonly used field bus technology is Bitbus.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Bitbus was created by Intel Corporation to enhance use of Multibus systems in industrial systems by separating slow i/o functions from faster memory access.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In 1983, Intel created the 8044 Bitbus microcontroller by adding field bus firmware to its existing 8051 microcontroller.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Bitbus uses EIA-485 at the physical layer, with two twisted pairs - one for data and the other for clocking and signals.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Use of SDLC at the data link layer permits 250 nodes on one segment with a total distance of 13.2 km.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Bitbus has one master node and multiple slaves, with slaves only responding to requests from the master.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Bitbus does not define routing at the network layer.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The 8044 permits only a relatively small data packet (13 bytes), but embeds an efficient set of RAC (remote access and control) tasks and the ability to develop custom RAC tasks.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In 1990, the IEEE adopted Bitbus as the Microcontroller System Serial Control Bus (IEEE-1118).
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Today BITBUS is maintained by the BEUG - BITBUS European Users Group.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Office networks are not really suited for automation applications, as they lack the upper-bounded transmission delay.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] ARCNET, which was conceived as early as 1975 for office connectivity uses a token mechanism and therefore found later uses in industry.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Automation Protocol (MAP) was an implementation of OSI-compliant protocols in automation technology initiated by General Motors in 1984.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] MAP became a LAN standardization proposal supported by many manufacturers and was mainly used in factory automation.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] MAP used the 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.4 token bus as a transmission medium.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Due to its scope and complexity, MAP failed to make a big breakthrough.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] To reduce the complexity and reach faster processing with reduced resources the Enhanced Performance Architecture (EPA) MAP was developed in 1988.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This MiniMap contains only levels 1, 2, and 7 of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) basic reference model.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This shortcut was taken over by later fieldbus definitions.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The most important achievement of MAP is Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS), the application layer of MAP.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS) is an international standard ISO 9506 dealing with an application protocol and services for transferring real time process data and supervisory control information between networked devices or computer applications published as a first version in 1986.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It has been a model for many further developments in other industrial communication standardizations such as FMS for Profibus or SDO for CANopen.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It is still in use as a possible application layer e.g. for power utility automation in the IEC 61850 standards.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In the field of manufacturing automation the requirements for a fieldbus are to support short reaction times with only a few bits or bytes to be transmitted over not more than some hundreds of meters.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In 1979 Modicon (now Schneider Electric) defined a serial bus to connect their programmable logic controllers (PLCs) called Modbus.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In its first version Modbus used a two wire cable with EIA 485 UART signals.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The protocol itself is very simple with a master/slave protocol and the number of data types are limited to those understood by PLCs at the time.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Nevertheless, Modbus is (with its Modbus-TCP version) still one of the most used industrial networks, mainly in the building automation field.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] A research project with the financial support of the German government defined in 1987 the fieldbus PROFIBUS based on the *Fieldbus Message Specification* (FMS).
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In practical applications, it proved too complicated to handle in the field.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In 1994 Siemens proposed a modified application layer with the name *Decentralized Periphery* (DP) which reached a good acceptance in the manufacturing industry.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] As of 2016, the Profibus is one of the most installed fieldbuses in the world and reached 60 million installed nodes in 2018.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In 1987 Phoenix Contact developed a serial bus to connect spatially distributed inputs and outputs to a centralized controller.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The controller sends one frame over a physical ring, which contains all input and output data.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The cable has 5 wires: besides the ground signal, two wires for the outgoing frame and two wires for the returning frame.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] With this cable is it possible to have the whole installation in a tree topology.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The INTERBUS was very successful in the manufacturing industry with more than 22,9 million devices installed in the field.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The Interbus joined the Profinet technology for Ethernet-based fieldbus Profinet and the INTERBUS is now maintained by the Profibus Nutzerorganisation e.V.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] During the 1980s, to solve communication problems between different control systems in cars, the German company Robert Bosch GmbH first developed the Controller Area Network (CAN).
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The concept of CAN was that every device can be connected by a single set of wires, and every device that is connected can freely exchange data with any other device.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] CAN soon migrated into the factory automation marketplace (with many others).
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In process automation traditionally most of the field transmitters are connected over a current loop with 4-20 mA to the controlling device.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This allows not only to transmit the measured value with the level of the current, but also provide the required electrical power to the field device with just one two-wire cable of a length of more than a thousand meters.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] These systems are also installed in hazardous areas.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] According to NAMUR a fieldbus in these applications has to fulfill these requirements.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] A special standard for instrumentation, IEC/EN 60079-27, describes requirements for the Fieldbus Intrinsically Safe Concept (FISCO) for installations in zone 0, 1 or 2.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The FIP standard is based on a French initiative in 1982 to create a requirements analysis for a future field bus standard.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The study led to the European Eureka initiative for a field bus standard in June 1986 that included 13 partners.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The development group (réseaux locaux industriels) created the first proposal to be standardized in France.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The name of the FIP field bus was originally given as an abbreviation of the French "Flux d'Information vers le Processus" while later referring to FIP with the English name "Factory Instrumentation Protocol".
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] FIP has lost ground to Profibus which came to prevail the market in Europe in the following decade - the WorldFIP homepage has seen no press release since 2002.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The closest cousin of the FIP family can be found today in the Wire Train Bus for train coaches.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] However a specific subset of WorldFIP - known the FIPIO protocol - can be found widely in machine components.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation (ISA) as SP50.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus today enjoys a growing installed base in many heavy process applications such as refining, petrochemicals, power generation, and even food and beverage, pharmaceuticals, and nuclear applications.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Effective January 1, 2015, the Fieldbus Foundation has become part of the new FieldComm Group.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Profibus PA (process automation) is used for communication between measuring and process instruments, actuators and process control system or PLC/DCS in process engineering.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Profibus PA is a Profibus version with physical layer suitable for process automation, in which several segments (PA segments) with field instruments can be connected to Profibus DP via so-called couplers.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The two-wire bus cable of these segments takes over not only the communication, but also the power supply of the participants (MBP transmission technology).
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Another special feature of Profibus PA is the widely used device profile "PA Devices" (PA Profile), in which the most important functions of the field devices are standardized across manufacturers.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The BatiBUS defined in 1989 and used mainly in France, the Instabus extended to the European Installation Bus (EIB) and the European Home Systems Protocol (EHS) merged in 1999 to the Konnex) (KNX) standard EN 50090, (ISO/IEC 14543-3).
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In 2020 495 Member companies offer 8'000 products with KNX interfaces in 190 countries worldwide.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Going back to the 1980s, unlike other networks, LonWorks is the result of the work of computer scientists from Echelon Corporation.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (ANSI/CEA-709.1-B), in 2005 as EN 14908 (European building automation standard).
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The BACnet standard was initially developed and is now maintained by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) starting in 1987.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] BACnet is an American National Standard (ANSI) 135 since 1995, a European standard, a national standard in many countries, and global ISO Standard 16484 since 2003.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] BACnet has in 2017 a market share of 60% in building automation market.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Although fieldbus technology has been around since 1988, with the completion of the ISA S50.02 standard, the development of the international standard took many years.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In 1999, the IEC SC65C/WG6 standards committee met to resolve difference in the draft IEC fieldbus standard.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The result of this meeting was the initial form of the IEC 61158 standard with eight different protocol sets called "Types".
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This form of standard was first developed for the European Common Market, concentrates less on commonality, and achieves its primary purpose—elimination of restraint of trade between nations.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Issues of commonality are now left to the international consortia that support each of the fieldbus standard types.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Almost as soon as it was approved, the IEC standards development work ceased and the committee was dissolved.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] A new IEC committee SC65C/MT-9 was formed to resolve the conflicts in form and substance within the more than 4000 pages of IEC 61158.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The work on the above protocol types is substantially complete.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] New protocols, such as for safety fieldbuses or real-time Ethernet fieldbuses are being accepted into the definition of the international fieldbus standard during a typical 5-year maintenance cycle.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In the 2008 version of the standard, the fieldbus types are reorganized into Communication Profile Families (CPFs).
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] There were many competing technologies for fieldbuses and the original hope for one single unified communications mechanism has not been realized.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This should not be unexpected since fieldbus technology needs to be implemented differently in different applications; automotive fieldbuses are functionally different from process plant control fieldbuses.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In June 1999 the IEC's Committee of Action (CA) decided to take a new structure for the fieldbus standards beginning with a first edition valid at the January 1, 2000, in time for the new millennium: There is a large IEC 61158 standard, where all fieldbuses find their place.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The experts have decided that the structure of IEC 61158 is maintained according to different layers, divided into services and protocols.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The individual fieldbuses are incorporated into this structure as different types.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Each part still contains several thousand pages.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Therefore, these parts have been further subdivided into subparts.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The individual protocols have simply been numbered with a type.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Each protocol type thus has its own subpart if required.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In order to find the corresponding subpart of the individual parts of the IEC 61158 standard, one must know the corresponding protocol type for a specific family.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In the 2019 edition of IEC 61158 up to 26 different types of protocols are specified.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In IEC 61158 standardization, the use of brand names is avoided and replaced by dry technical terms and abbreviations.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] For example, Ethernet is replaced by the technically correct CSMA/CD or a reference to the corresponding ISO standard 8802.3.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This is also the case with fieldbus names, they all are replaced by type numbers.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The reader will therefore never find a designation such as PROFIBUS or DeviceNet in the entire IEC 61158 fieldbus standard.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In the section Compliance to IEC 61784 a complete reference table is provided.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It is clear that this collection of fieldbus standards in IEC 61158 is not suitable for implementation.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It must be supplemented with instructions for use.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] These instructions show how and which parts of IEC 61158 can be assembled to a functioning system.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This assembly instruction has been compiled subsequently as IEC 61784 fieldbus profiles.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The IEC 61784 Part 1 standard with the name *Profile sets for continuous and discrete manufacturing relative to fieldbus use in industrial control systems* lists all fieldbuses which are proposed by the national standardization bodies.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Swiftnet, which is widely used in aircraft construction (Boeing), was included in the first edition of the standard.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This later proves to be a mistake and in the 2007 edition 2 this protocol was removed from the standard.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] At the same time, the CPF 8 CC-Link, the CPF 9 HART protocol and CPF 16 SERCOS are added.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In the edition 4 in 2014 the last fieldbus CPF 19 MECHATROLINK was included into the standard.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The edition 5 in 2019 was just a maintenance revision without any new profile added.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] See List of automation protocols for fieldbuses that are not included in this standard.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Already in edition 2 of the fieldbus profile first profiles based on Ethernet as physical layer are included.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] All this new developed Real-time Ethernet (RTE) protocols are compiled in IEC 61784 Part 2 as *Additional profiles for ISO/IEC 8802 3 based communication networks in real-time applications*.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The SERCOS solution is interesting in this context.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This network from the field of axis control had its own standard IEC 61491.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] With the introduction of the Ethernet-based solution SERCOS III, this standard has been taken apart and the communication part is integrated in IEC 61158/61784.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The application part has been integrated together with other drive solutions into a special drive standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In 2010, a second edition was published to include CPF 17 RAPIEnet and CPF 18 SafetyNET p.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In the third edition (2014), the Industrial Ethernet (IE) version of CC-Link was added.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The two profile families CPF 20 ADS-net and CPF 19 FL-net were added to the fourth edition in 2019.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] For details about these RTEs see the article on Industrial Ethernet.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] For functional safety, different consortia have developed different protocols for safety applications up to Safety Integrity Level 3 (SIL) according to IEC 61508 or Performance Level "e" (PL) according to ISO 13849.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] What most solutions have in common is that they are based on a *Black Channel* and can therefore be transmitted via different fieldbuses and networks.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Depending on the actual profile the safety protocol does provide measures like counters, CRCs, echo, timeout, unique sender and receiver IDs or cross check.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] SERCOS does use the *CIP safety* protocol as well.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In the third edition in 2016 the last safety profile CPF 17 SafetyNET p was added.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] A new edition 4 is expected to be published in 2021.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The standard has now 9 different safety profiles.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] They are all included and referenced in the global compliance table in the next section.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The protocol families of each brand name are called Communication Profile Family and are abbreviated as CPF with a number.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Each protocol family can now define fieldbuses, real-time Ethernet solutions, installation rules and protocols for functional safety.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] These possible profile families are laid down in IEC 61784 and compiled in the following table.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] As an example, we will search for the standards for PROFIBUS-DP.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This belongs to the CPF 3 family and has the profile CP 3/1.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In Table 5 we find that its protocol scope is defined in IEC 61784 Part 1.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The physical interface is defined in the common 61158-2 under type 3.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The installation regulations can be found in IEC 61784-5-3 in Appendix A.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It can be combined with the FSCP3/1 as PROFIsafe, which is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] To avoid the manufacturer having to list all these standards explicitly, the reference to the profile is specified in the standard.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Discrete fieldbus networks are often referred to as "device networks".
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Already in the year 2000 the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) decided that a set of *controller-device interfaces* (CDIs) will be specified by the Technical Committee TC 121 *Low-voltage switchgear and controlgear* to cover the device networks.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The amount of cabling required is much lower in fieldbus than in 4–20 mA installations.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] This is because many devices share the same set of cables in a multi-dropped fashion rather than requiring a dedicated set of cables per device as in the case of 4–20 mA devices.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Moreover, several parameters can be communicated per device in a fieldbus network whereas only one parameter can be transmitted on a 4–20 mA connection.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] A fieldbus also provides a good foundation for the creation of a predictive and proactive maintenance strategy.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The diagnostics available from fieldbus devices can be used to address issues with devices before they become critical problems.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Despite each technology sharing the generic name of fieldbus the various fieldbuses are not readily interchangeable.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The differences between them are so profound that they cannot be easily connected to each other.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] To understand the differences among fieldbus standards, it is necessary to understand how fieldbus networks are designed.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] With reference to the OSI model, fieldbus standards are determined by the physical media of the cabling, and layers one, two and seven of the reference model.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] For each technology the physical medium and the physical layer standards fully describe, in detail, the implementation of bit timing, synchronization, encoding/decoding, band rate, bus length and the physical connection of the transceiver to the communication wires.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The data link layer standard is responsible for fully specifying how messages are assembled ready for transmission by the physical layer, error handling, message-filtering and bus arbitration and how these standards are to be implemented in hardware.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] The application layer standard, in general defines how the data communication layers are interfaced to the application that wishes to communicate.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It describes message specifications, network management implementations and response to the request from the application of services.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Layers three to six are not described in fieldbus standards.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Different fieldbuses offer different sets of features and performance.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] It is difficult to make a general comparison of fieldbus performance because of fundamental differences in data transfer methodology.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] In the comparison table below it is simply noted if the fieldbus in question typically supports data update cycles of 1 millisecond or faster.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] As of 2008, in process control systems, the market is dominated by Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Both technologies use the same physical layer (2-wire Manchester-encoded current modulation at 31.25 kHz) but are not interchangeable.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] As a general guide, applications which are controlled and monitored by programmable logic controllers (PLCs) tend towards PROFIBUS, and applications which are controlled and monitored by a digital/distributed control system (DCS) tend towards Foundation Fieldbus.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] PROFIBUS technology is made available through Profibus International with headquarters in Karlsruhe, Germany.
[src:ethercat/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is owned and distributed by the Fieldbus Foundation of Austin, Texas.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet can also refer to the use of standard Ethernet protocols with rugged connectors and extended temperature switches in an industrial environment, for automation or process control.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] Components used in plant process areas must be designed to work in harsh environments of temperature extremes, humidity, and vibration that exceed the ranges for information technology equipment intended for installation in controlled environments.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] The use of fiber-optic Ethernet variants reduces the problems of electrical noise and provides electrical isolation.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] Some industrial networks emphasized deterministic delivery of transmitted data, whereas Ethernet used collision detection which made transport time for individual data packets difficult to estimate with increasing network traffic.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] Typically, industrial uses of Ethernet employ full-duplex standards and other methods so that collisions do not unacceptably influence transmission times.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] Industrial use requires consideration of the environment in which the equipment must operate.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] Factory equipment must tolerate a wider range of temperature, vibration, physical contamination and electrical noise than equipment installed in dedicated information-technology wiring closets.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] Since critical process control may rely on an Ethernet link, the economic cost of interruptions may be high and high availability is therefore an essential criterion.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet networks must interoperate with both current and legacy systems, and must provide predictable performance and maintainability.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] In addition to physical compatibility and low-level transport protocols, a practical industrial Ethernet system must also provide interoperability of higher levels of the OSI model.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] An industrial network must provide security both from intrusions from outside the plant, and inadvertent or unauthorized use within the plant.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] When an industrial network must connect to an office network or external networks, a firewall system can be inserted to control exchange of data between the networks.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] This network separation preserves the performance and reliability of the industrial network.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) communicate using one of several possible open or proprietary protocols, such as EtherNet/IP, EtherCAT, Modbus, Sinec H1, Profibus, CANopen, DeviceNet or FOUNDATION Fieldbus.
[src:ethercat/industrial-ethernet] The idea to use standard Ethernet makes these systems more interoperable.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] Typically the position or velocity of machines are controlled using some type of device such as a hydraulic pump, linear actuator, or electric motor, generally a servo.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] Motion control is an important part of robotics and CNC machine tools, however in these instances it is more complex than when used with specialized machines, where the kinematics are usually simpler.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] The latter is often called General Motion Control (GMC).
[src:ethercat/motion-control] Motion control is widely used in the packaging, printing, textile, semiconductor production, and assembly industries.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] Motion Control encompasses every technology related to the movement of objects.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] It covers every motion system from micro-sized systems such as silicon-type micro induction actuators to micro-siml systems such as a space platform.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] But, these days, the focus of motion control is the special control technology of motion systems with electric actuators such as dc/ac servo motors.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] Control of robotic manipulators is also included in the field of motion control because most of robotic manipulators are driven by electrical servo motors and the key objective is the control of motion.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] The interface between the motion controller and drives it control is very critical when coordinated motion is required, as it must provide tight synchronization.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] Historically the only open interface was an analog signal, until open interfaces were developed that satisfied the requirements of coordinated motion control, the first being SERCOS in 1991 which is now enhanced to SERCOS III.
[src:ethercat/motion-control] Later interfaces capable of motion control include Ethernet/IP, Profinet IRT, Ethernet Powerlink, and EtherCAT.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:ethercat/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
